At the close oi this paragraph naturalia praecepta are distinguished from praecepta gentium and praecepta civilia: so in the next Title ius naturale is distinguished from both ius gentium andins civile. This, however, is (with two exceptions, Bk. i. 2. 2, ib. 5. pr.) the only passage in the Institutas in which ius gentium is opposed to ius naturale, and it leaves no mark on the system: in all other places the two expressions are used as synonymous, and in Bk. ii. 1. 11 they are expressly identified, ⁴. . . iure naturali, quod, sicut diximus, appellatur ius gentium’ The explanation of the seeming anomaly is that in Tit. r. 4, and Tit. 2. pr. Justinian is quoting verbatim lrom the institutes of Ulpian, who is the only leading jurist who makes anything of the distinction, while Tit. 2. pr. is taken from Gaius.
